{"chunk_id": "b79855a8-6924-4454-b988-41898e1fd808", "source_database": "ICMR", "document_title": "ICMR_NIN_Dietary_Guidelines_Real.pdf", "publication_version": "Latest", "chunk_sequence_number": 224, "content_type": "Medical Guideline", "language": "English", "text": "specially useful or feeding infants, toddlers, growing children and expectant women and nursing mothers. All the macro and micro-nutrients are present in an easily digestible and assimilable form in milk. Milk proteins possess high biological value which is almost equal to that of meat, eggs and other high- quality animal proteins. Milk proteins are valuable supplements to most vegetarian diets. Milk is a rich source of bioavailable calcium which helps in the building up of strong bones. Milk fat serves as a vehicle for important fat-soluble vitamins A, D and E. Since, milk fat is of the saturated type those who have to be on a low fat diet can consume skimmed/toned milk. For strict vegetarians, milk is the only source of vitamin B . Milk is also rich in riboflavin, but is a poor source of", "embedding": [0.008544485084712505, -0.06700075417757034, -0.04256359487771988, 0.02744264341890812, 0.05603768303990364, 0.03785768151283264, -5.019867603550665e-05, 0.07587084919214249, -0.01912485994398594, -0.027188600972294807, -0.03800542280077934, -0.0011756126768887043, -0.06744150817394257, 0.00890868715941906, 0.06285463273525238, 0.007308598607778549, 0.07557167112827301, 0.08587663620710373, -0.016351236030459404, -0.02547955885529518, -0.018008945509791374, -0.041588637977838516, 0.025817926973104477, 0.033999964594841, 0.04468698427081108, -0.04863071069121361, 0.03577490523457527, -0.07857885211706161, 0.012627344578504562, 0.03383816406130791, -0.02912968210875988, -0.11961015313863754, 0.08002204447984695, -0.05999693647027016, -0.07161594182252884, 0.052058394998311996, 0.10647095739841461, -0.07676755636930466, -0.03924999013543129, -0.07478950917720795, 0.043564967811107635, 0.01740540936589241